1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:03,134
SPEAKER_00: The 737 MAX was sold as a familiar airplane.

2
00:00:03,915 --> 00:00:05,177
SPEAKER_00: That was the commercial promise.

3
00:00:06,099 --> 00:00:10,826
SPEAKER_00: Airlines could keep crews, schedules, and training close to the old 737.

4
00:00:11,567 --> 00:00:16,312
SPEAKER_00: Then Boeing put larger CFM Leap engines on the aircraft.

5
00:00:17,254 --> 00:00:24,704
SPEAKER_00: They sat farther forward and higher on the wing, and under certain high angle of attack conditions, the jet could pitch up differently.

6
00:00:25,207 --> 00:00:34,036
SPEAKER_00: MCAS was built to make that new behavior feel familiar, but the system could move the stabilizer from one angle of attack sensor.

7
00:00:35,076 --> 00:00:37,840
SPEAKER_00: Pilots were not clearly trained that it existed by name.

8
00:00:39,240 --> 00:00:45,707
SPEAKER_00: After Lionair 610, the warning still was not reclassified fast enough as an architectural problem.

9
00:00:46,508 --> 00:00:47,628
SPEAKER_00: The plane had changed.

10
00:00:48,590 --> 00:00:51,031
SPEAKER_00: The story told to the people flying it had not.

11
00:00:51,832 --> 00:00:54,996
SPEAKER_00: Small causes, massive consequences.
